{
  "headers": [
    {
      "source": "/(.*).html",
      "headers": [
        {
          "key": "Content-Type",
          "value": "text/html; charset=utf-8"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "/",
      "headers": [
        {
          "key": "Content-Type",
          "value": "text/html; charset=utf-8"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

---

## Why This Happens

When a browser receives a file, it doesn't just "look" at it — it reads the `Content-Type` header from the server to decide **how to render it**. If that header says `text/plain`, the browser displays raw text. If it says `text/html`, the browser parses and renders it as a webpage.

Vercel was serving your file without the correct header, so the browser said "this is just text, I'll display it as-is" — which is exactly what you saw.

